officers, judges, and parents and friends of addicts in one West Virginia town, William Garriott finds that this overriding effort to confront the problem changed the character of the community as well as the role of law in creating and maintaining social order. Ultimately, this work addresses the impact of methamphetamine and, more generally, the war on drugs, on everyday life in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDrug trafficxInvestigationxWest Virginia. 0aDrug trafficxInvestigationzWest Virginia. 0aMethamphetamine abusexPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aMethamphetamine abusexPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aMethamphetamine abusexPreventionxWest Virginia. 0aMethamphetamine abusezWest VirginiaxPrevention. 0aMethamphetaminexWest Virginia. 0aMethamphetaminezWest Virginia. 0aPolicexUnited States. 0aPolicezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814733004.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814733004zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814733004/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA